'{"corrected_text":"HINTS OF FASHION, Linen suits are principally cut with a skirt and polonaise, the latter generally the Marguerite. All the new over-pkirts are made long very long at the back, but draped high at the sides, with the apron front. Black striped grenadine bias ruffles may be used as trimmings; striped organdy bias ruffles or bias bands, edged with lace. Now tinted scarlet for evening wear are composed of twilled silk, with wide diagonal stripe, shaded from dark to light in the shingle color. Kid embroidery wrought in the linen is now the fashionable method of ornamenting underclothing, and is much more suitable as well as more durable than lace or milling. Neck ties or bow are of pale twilled silk, with or without fringed ends, the fringe forming knotted tassels. Others are of twilled silk edged with Valen¬ cien¬ nes, the ends forming a cascade com¬ potted of alternate shades of silk and lace. As the warm weather advances many different styles for suits will be introduced, but the skirt and the polonaise will be mainly adhered to, and the simpler the design for washing materials the better it looks, and the longer it retains its tresh\' appearance. Satin striped organdy is a novelty in white muslin ; the stripes are an inch broad and have a sun finished surface. It "does up" nicely and will make pretty summer suits or house dresse, and it will need but little trimming. Black satin striped grenadine is used this season in blond of the Vixck with a white stripe, which was in much in vogue last year. Of course both will be worn, but the all black is later and considered more lady like. GLEANINGS. It is reported that there are seventy-five counties in Texas in which there is not a single Sunday school.","has_modifications":true}'
